:"guid";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=4227";s:8:"comments";s:105:"http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=slideshare-oembed#comments";s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:101:"http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=slideshare-oembedfeed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sun, 22 May 2011 07:50:53 +0100";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Joost de Valk";}s:8:"category";s:36:"WordPressSlideShareWordPress Plugins";s:11:"description";s:748:"<p>Last week at SAScon, Bas pointed out to me that SlideShare has a new embed method using an iframe instead of the old fashioned object stuff. So I started updating my SlideShare plugin, and when I was browsing the documentation I noticed they\'d also added support for oEmbed since I looked at it. The funny [...]</p><p><a href="http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/">SlideShare plugin, now with oEmbed</a> is a post from <a href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>. \n\nA good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don\'t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:1860:"<p>Last week at <a title="Presentations from SAScon" href="http://yoast.com/presentations-from-sascon/">SAScon</a>, <a href="http://www.stateofsearch.com/">Bas</a> pointed out to me that SlideShare has a new embed method using an iframe instead of the old fashioned object stuff. So I started updating my <a title="SlideShare WordPress plugin" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress/slideshare/">SlideShare plugin</a>, and when I was browsing the documentation I noticed they\'d also added support for oEmbed since I looked at it.</p>\n<p>The funny thing is that their oEmbed API still returns the old code, and that\'s there\'s no good way to tell up front which width you want for the presentation to be embedded. So I had to hack around a bit, but it works now: the plugin now uses oEmbed to retrieve the correct ID for the presentation and then transforms it into a player of the new style, with the width your theme supports. This means that all you have to do now is enable the URL and enter a SlideShare URL on a line of it\'s own and it\'ll be embedded.</p>\n<p>To be honest though, I\'ve found that this is a bit slowish and using the WordPress.com embed code (available under embed -&gt; customize) is still a more reliable and faster embed method. If you use the plugin, be sure to grab the updated SlideShare plugin, now at version 1.8.</p>\n<p><a href="http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/">SlideShare plugin, now with oEmbed</a> is a post from <a href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>. \n\nA good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don\'t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/fuHtqORcF9Y" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:96:"http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=slideshare-oembed";}s:7:"summary";s:748:"<p>Last week at SAScon, Bas pointed out to me that SlideShare has a new embed method using an iframe instead of the old fashioned object stuff. So I started updating my SlideShare plugin, and when I was browsing the documentation I noticed they\'d also added support for oEmbed since I looked at it. The funny [...]</p><p><a href="http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/">SlideShare plugin, now with oEmbed</a> is a post from <a href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>. \n\nA good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don\'t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:1860:"<p>Last week at <a title="Presentations from SAScon" href="http://yoast.com/presentations-from-sascon/">SAScon</a>, <a href="http://www.stateofsearch.com/">Bas</a> pointed out to me that SlideShare has a new embed method using an iframe instead of the old fashioned object stuff. So I started updating my <a title="SlideShare WordPress plugin" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress/slideshare/">SlideShare plugin</a>, and when I was browsing the documentation I noticed they\'d also added support for oEmbed since I looked at it.</p>\n<p>The funny thing is that their oEmbed API still returns the old code, and that\'s there\'s no good way to tell up front which width you want for the presentation to be embedded. So I had to hack around a bit, but it works now: the plugin now uses oEmbed to retrieve the correct ID for the presentation and then transforms it into a player of the new style, with the width your theme supports. This means that all you have to do now is enable the URL and enter a SlideShare URL on a line of it\'s own and it\'ll be embedded.</p>\n<p>To be honest though, I\'ve found that this is a bit slowish and using the WordPress.com embed code (available under embed -&gt; customize) is still a more reliable and faster embed method. If you use the plugin, be sure to grab the updated SlideShare plugin, now at version 1.8.</p>\n<p><a href="http://yoast.com/slideshare-oembed/">SlideShare plugin, now with oEmbed</a> is a post from <a href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>. \n\nA good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don\'t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/fuHtqORcF9Y" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:6;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:25:"Presentations from SAScon";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/joostdevalk/~3/795Wj3fYuus/";s:4:"guid";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=4225";s:8:"comments";s:121:"http://yoast.com/presentations-from-sascon/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=presentations-from-sascon#comments";s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:117:"http://yoast.com/presentations-from-sascon/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=presentations-from-sasconfeed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"6";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sun, 22 May 2011 07:32:57 +0100";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Joost de Valk";}s:8:"category";s:84:"Online MarketingConferencehreviewMicroformatsSEO toolsWordPress PluginsWordPress SEO";s:11:"description";s:783:"<p>This thursday and friday was the time for SAScon in Manchester, where I gave 3 formal presentations, I\'ve embedded them here (using an updated SlideShare plugin, more on that in the next post): Feeds &#38; Microformats This panel, together with Richard Baxter of SEOgadget and James Lowery of Latitude, contained some great discussion on how [...]</p><p><a href="http://yoast.com/presentations-from-sascon/">Presentations from SAScon</a> is a post from <a href="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a href="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>. \n\nA good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don\'t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a href="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2167:"<p>This thursday and friday was the time for <a href="http://www.sascon.co.uk/">SAScon</a> in Manchester, where I gave 3 formal presentations, I\'ve embedded them here (using an updated <a title="SlideShare WordPress plugin" href="http://yoast.com/wordpress/slideshare/">SlideShare plugin</a>, more on that in the next post):</p>\n<h2>Feeds &amp; Microformats</h2>\n<p>This panel,